    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-10-18T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-10-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="788"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d788">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/1176: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wadsworth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-10-18T15:00:00+02:00"
                            >October 18, 1938—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 4:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Associated Press and other news agency cables effectively portray state of
                    intense tension following rebel control Old City Jerusalem except Jaffa Gate
                    area and Armenian and Jewish quarters.</p>
                <p>Persistent long range sniping between military surrounding disaffected area and
                    rebel occupants continues but thus far I am informed by Government press officer
                    no deaths either side are known.</p>
                <p>As yet no decision taken by military as to how to regain control. To send troops
                    into maze narrow bazaars would entail heavy casualties but this appears to be
                    only course open. There is no question bombardment similar Damascus 1925.<note
                        n="83" xml:id="d788fn83">See section entitled “Precautions by the United
                        States for the Safety of Americans During the Syrian Insurrection,” <ref
                            target="frus1925v02#pg_105">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1925, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, pp. 105</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wadsworth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
